==FOREWORD==
	There have not been many native Tibetan dictionaries.  The few that were made in earlier times were almost unusable because they were written in a style that did not allow for easy look-up of terms.  In the 20th century, three dictionaries were made that were, for the first time, usable as dictionaries.  The first was made in Lhasa in the 1940?s prior to the Communist takeover.  It was the dictionary presented here, made by Geshe Chodrak with the assistance of the remarkably erudite and modern scholar, Gendun Chophel.  The two other major dictionaries were made in the 1970?s and 1980?s after the Communist takeover; they are the dag yig gsar sgrigs New Style Compilation Pure Letters and bod rgya tshig mdzod chen mo The Great Tibetan-Chinese Dictionary.
	All three dictionaries are useful.  However, the two later dictionaries have both been considerably influenced by Chinese thought and needs, often in a way detrimental to the contents of the dictionary.  Geshe Chodrak?s dictionary on the other hand has was written in a purely Tibetan situation without another culture overseeing the work and insisting on changes that suited its own needs.
	Geshe Chodrak?s dictionary is not as useful as the other two dictionaries when it comes to verbs.  The other two dictionaries lay out all of the tense forms for each verb and do a much better job of it.  (For the serious student, the best reference for Tibetan verbs these days is not the Tibetan dictionaries mentioned above but The Illuminator Tibetan-English Dictionary which makes a special point of presenting all Tibetan verbs in the most complete and correct way possible.)
	Geshe Chodrak?s dictionary features short but precise definitions.  It should be extremely useful to students of the language at all levels.  It will be particularly useful for students who are advanced enough to want to start using a Tibetan-Tibetan dictionary but who cannot penetrate the difficult and terse language of The Great Tibetan-Chinese Dictionary.
	Geshe Chodrak?s dictionary is the latest in the output from the Padma Karpo Translation Committee.  For some years I have steered the committee towards making a series of electronic Tibetan lexicons so that scholars and translators could have reliable and easy-to-use references for their work.  With the presentation of Geshe Chodrak?s dictionary, we now offer: The Illuminator Tibetan-English Dictionary a thoroughly reliable and modern Tibetan-English dictionary written by myself; the classic Sarat Chandra Das?s Tibetan-English Dictionary in a new, edited edition; the official Sanskrit-Tibetan vocabulary made by the early Tibetan translators The Mah?vyutpatti; and now a major, Tibetan-Tibetan dictionary to round out the offering.

With our best wishes,
Tony Duff,
Director of Padma Karpo Translation Committee,
24th January, 2013
Kathmandu,
NEPAL
==DICTIONARY AND VERBS==
	This dictionary does not present verbs in a highly ordered way though it does follow Tibetan grammar in its presentation of verbs.  You will find a much better presentation of verbs in The Illuminator Tibetan-English Dictionary.
	Note that Geshe Chodrak uses the standard grammatical devices to indicate verb tenses.  The use of zin pa after a verb shows that the past tense meaning is being indicated.  The use of bzhin pa after a verb shows that the (usually present) continuous tense meaning is being indicated.
	Note that Tibetan verb theory is moderately complex.  It is considerably compounded by the variations in spelling that existed in Tibet.  And it is compounded even further by the fact that the bulk of Tibetan manuscripts were prepared by scribes who were not always great scholars.  Thus in Tibetan literature, there are both abundant variations in the ways of writing verbs and their tenses, many of which are mistaken.  Earlier compilers of Tibetan English dictionaries often compiled their works by looking through Tibetan texts and taking the spellings that they found and assumed that they were correct or worthy of an entry in the dictionary.  Because of this, every non-native Tibetan dictionary that I know of included spelling errors, especially of verbs.  For example, Sarat Chandra Das?s Tibetan-English Dictionary is an excellent dictionary in many ways but has many errors in its listing of verbs.  Native dictionaries tend not have this fault, as might be expected.  However, Geshe Chodrak has included some verb tense forms which are not usually accepted as correct.  Again, for a complete and correct listing, see The Illuminator Tibetan-English Dictionary.
==TRANSLITERATED VERSION==
	We have produced two versions of the new electronic edition of Geshe Chodrak?s Tibetan-Tibetan Dictionary.  The first version uses Tibetan script throughout to display the Tibetan text.  Some non-Tibetans find that difficult to use, so we have produced this, second version.  In it, all Tibetan script is rendered in transliterated Tibetan.  Please note the following:
	? Where needed, to distinguish Tibetan transliteration from English, the transliterated text is underlined.
	? All lookups and searches can be done simply by typing Tibetan in transliteration.
	? The transliteration system is Wylie?s system, with some extensions.  Click here to go to the section TIBETAN TRANSLITERATION SYSTEM q.v.  (All blue-coloured text in this electronic text is hypertext, meaning that you can click on it and jump to that entry).
	? The Tibetan script of the headwords has been added to the top of each definition to increasd the usefulness of the dictionary.  It is marked off with an arrow and is then followed by the definition, which is also marked off by an arrow.
	? If you are a serious student of the Tibetan language, we would like to offer the advice that it is better to persevere with the non-transliterated version of the dictionary.  Learning to read and type the Tibetan text directly will greatly improve your comprehension of the language.
If you would prefer to use the non-transliterated version, please start it from its own icon on the desktop or from the menu.
==SOFTWARE TIPS AND SHORTCUTS==
	The dictionary is accessed with the new TibetD software designed and programmed by Mr. Tony Duff and his translation committee.  This software is highly suited to presenting Tibetan and English in electronic form and is especially made to serve the needs of electronic dictionaries.  If you learn the features of the software, you will find that you have a very powerful tool on your hands.

How can you learn the software?
	? First and foremost, the built-in help is a complete book written to be a clear guide to the use of the software.  Press F1 in order to read the book.  The first several sections are most important because they give you a basic guide to the use of the software, including a complete description of how the navigation keys work.
	? Second, the help contains a complete section with extremely detailed instructions on how to type Tibetan.  You have the choice of using a Wylie-style keyboard or a standard keyboard for Tibetan.  If you wish to use the standard Tibetan keyboard, you can get a map of the Tibetan keyboard by pressing help and then choosing ?Tibetan keyboard map?.  You can print this map and keep it with you until you learn the keyboard or you can keep it up on the screen while you are using the dictionary.

		Also, please do not think that the standard Tibetan keyboard is hard to learn.  We made it extremely easy; you can learn it within half an hour if you try.  The whole thing is summed up as follows: a) all of the consonants are listed in order across the keyboard (ka kha ga nga etc.), so even if you don?t remember them you can still calculate where they are without looking at the map. b) The vowels are all placed in the center of the keyboard in Tibetan order (i u e o).  c) All of the stacked letters are made by first pressing the stack key (h) which is at the very centre of the keyboard, then typing the letters of the stack.  This includes all of the Sanskrit stacks, too, so there is nothing else to learn.  d) Finally, you can access any letter in the Tibetan fonts by using the symbols window Ctrl+A.  Learning to type Tibetan really is that simple.

How to look up a word?
	Train yourself to use the dictionary as follows.  There are three, main ways to find something:
	ƒê Start by using the headword search feature.  To use it, type your word directly into the headword field (that?s the text box immediately above this text box).  As you new type each letter, the software will jump to the word that you have typed or the closest thing to it.  It will often arrive on the word you are looking for even before you have typed the whole word.  If you type the word correctly but it does not come up, then what you typed is not an entry in the dictionary.
	? The value of the headword search is that it allows you to find any main entry in the dictionary almost immediately.  However, the headword search feature only finds words at the headword level.  If you type something and do not find it at the headword level, there is still a very good chance that it is somewhere in the dictionary.  So the next step is to look through the whole dictionary, everywhere in both headwords and definitions.

	ƒê Next, use the search feature.  Press F2 or Ctrl+F to bring up in the search dialogue.  You can type any combination of Tibetan, English, and/or text with Sanskrit diacriticals in the search box.  You can use the controls of the search box to search in headwords, definitions, or both.  There are many other controls too end these are all described in the help section.
	? For example, to look up a Tibetan word anywhere in the dictionary, type the word in the search box and press the find button.
	? A big hint for searching is not to type everything but only to type a short string.  Especially, do not to type the tsheg normally required in Tibetan text at the very end of the string.  Some words will be in the dictionary followed by a shad rather than a tsheg, so if you always type a tsheg at the end of a Tibetan word, you will sometimes not find words that are in the dictionary.
	? To repeat a search, do NOT press F2 or Ctrl+F again.  Use F3 for repeating a search.  The reason is that, when you first start a search you can make lots of choices about how to do the search; when you press F2 or Ctrl+F you lose those choices but when you press F3 those choices are retained.
	? Searches are cyclic.  That means you can start a search anywhere and the software will search all the way to the bottom of the dictionary and then from the top down to your present position without your having to do anything more.
	? Any text in the software that has been selected will automatically be copied into the search box.  You gain use this as an easy way to put text into the box, especially Tibetan text.
	? What if you want to go backwards to a previous entry that you have already looked at?  Easy, use F4 and Shift+F4 to go forwards and backwards through the last 30 entries that you have looked at.

	ƒê Finally, there are several other ways to look up text in the dictionary.
	?   Any Tibetan text that it appears in the definitions can be used for doing searches or lookups.  You can select Tibetan or English text a word at a time simply by clicking on it with the mouse (there a keyboard shortcuts too?look up the keyboard shortcuts in help).  Once the text is selected, right click on it with the mouse to get a menu of options, including an option to do a direct look up on that word.
	? Or, once the text is selected, start a search.  The selected text will be put straight into the search box and you can use the features of the search box to make an effective search.
	? You can paste text into the headword field.  As soon as you paste it, the software will do a look up on it!  So, for example, you can select some text in a definition field, copy it to the clipboard (Ctrl+C or right mouse menu), and past it into the headword field.  If the text is not exactly what you want, you can edit the text in the headword field to get what you want.

You are reluctant to learn to type Tibetan?
	? Use the Wylie keyboard instead of the standard Tibetan keyboards.
	? Try using the transliterated version of the dictionary.
	? Or, in the standard dictionary with Tibetan text headwords, you can take advantage of the fact that all entries also have the headword in transliterated English.  You can use the search feature and type transliterated English instead of Tibetan.  Then find the entry you want that way.
	? The transliteration scheme used in here is very similar to but slightly different from Wylie?s system.  You can find all the details in the prefatory section called TIBETAN TRANSLITERATION SYSTEM.

Moving through the dictionary
	? There are many, many ways to move through the dictionary.  These are all described at length in the early parts of the help section.  Please read that section!
	? You have found an entry and now you want to go back to a previous entry?  Use F4 and Shift+F4 to go forwards and backwards through the last 30 entries that you have looked at.
	? You want to scroll down through the contents of the dictionary.  Make sure your cursor is in the headword field then press the arrow keys to move up or down one entry at the time.  Press the page up or page down keys to move several entries at a time.  Or, use the scroll bars to the right side of the panel.  Or, use the keyboard shortcuts to go to the top or bottom of the dictionary.  Etc, etc.
	? You want to scroll down through the contents of the current entry.  You can use the TAB key to jump from the headword field into the definition field or you can click on the definition field with a mouse.  Once you are in the definition field, you can use standard keys to move backwards and forwards up and down throughout the entry.  The definition field is actually a word processing screen with standard controls for it.
	? You want to return to the head field.  Either click on the headword field with the mouse or press Ctrl+TAB.
	? You want to see the current entry in the context of previous and succeeding entries in the dictionary.  The software defaults to this mode but try pressing F9 a couple of times and you will see how to change the screen.

Learn the shortcuts!
	? The mouse key is very powerful.  You can use it to select text and then look up the text.  Put your mouse over a Tibetan word and click once, then twice, and so forth.  The word will be selected intertsheg by intertsheg (the correct name for what is often incorrectly called a ?syllable?.  Now right click with the mouse and look at the possibilities.  If you click on the first option you can look up the word you have highlighted directly in the dictionary!
	? Use the bookmarks to mark your place while you go somewhere else.  E.g., mark this spot here by pressing F5, then a number from 1 to 4.  Go around somewhere else in the dictionary then return to this exact spot by pressing Alt plus the bookmark numeral just chosen.

Use the Hypertext!
	? One of the key features of this dictionary is that it is has copious hypertexting.  Anytime you see a coloured entry like this sangs rgyas simply click on it to jump to its definition.  When you have read the definition, if you wish to return, press F4.  Try it now!  The hypertexting takes this from being a simple dictionary to a very powerful learning tool.

Selecting Records
	There is a feature called the ?Select? feature.  If you press Ctrl+F2 instead of F2  you will get a dialogue box that looks exactly like the search box but which says ?Select? at the top instead of ?Find?.  If you type some text to search for and press Enter, instead of doing a normal search, the software will find all of the entries that contain the string you searched for and will make them into a small database sitting on top of the main one.  That way you will have a mini database that contains only the words you are looking for.  This allows you to collect together all the entries containing some particular text.
	You can repeat this is many times as you want to make specialized databases.  For example, you could make a database containing only the verbs using this process.  Or, you could make a database containing only the transitive or intransitive verbs.  When you are finished with a specialized database, you can get rid of it using one of the appropriate items on the search menu.  Or, you can use it as a basis for another select.
	All of the controls for the select feature are found on the Search menu on the menu bar.

Special Features when using multiple dictionaries
	We sell a number of dictionaries and Tibetan texts all in this the same format.  If you have the number of these running at once, you can do some fancy things.
	? You can cut and paste between dictionaries and texts and word processors such as TibetDoc.  That way you can make your own dictionaries or notes in TibetDoc.
	? You can take a word from a dictionary or text and look it up in another dictionary.  For example, you are using this dictionary and you are also the The Illuminator Tibetan-English dictionary.  You have looked up a word in this dictionary.  Now you want to see it in The Illuminator.  Copy the word(s) to the clipboard with Ctrl+C, switchover to The Illuminator with Alt+TAB, paste the words from the clipboard into the headword field with Ctrl+V.  As soon as you paste the words, the lookup is done and you will find the entry into the dictionary.  Alternatively, you might be looking at a Tibetan text; simply copy a word that you don?t know to the clipboard, switch to this or another dictionary, paste a word and the lookup happens immediately.  Each of our products is very useful in its own right but when combined with others you have a very powerful tool for scholarship and research.

	Those are the main points though there are many minor details, too.  If you study the software manual which is contained in the help section completely, then you will know all of these details.
==DICTIONARY CONVENTIONS==
The arrangement of the dictionary is very simple:
	1) Each headword has a short definition.  Multiple meanings within the definition are usually just separated by the term dang.

	2) Many definitions are ended with la?ang /.  This is a standard Tibetan device meaning ?this headword is also known as or written as or understood as ....?. 

	3) The original has a very large number of cases where two or more headwords are grouped together and given one definition.  This means that they share a definition but the dictionary is not in alphabetical order.  To deal with this:
		i) we put all entries in their correct alphabetic order.
		ii) we chose one member of each set of grouped entries as the principal entry for the group and put the definition with that.
		iii) we connected all of the other entries in the set to the principal entry.  We connected them by giving the principal entry of the set followed by the words dang don ?brel ba/.  This literally means ?of related meaning?.  We chose this wording because sometimes the members of a set are of the same meaning and sometimes of similar or related meaning.  To make it easy to find the definition we put a hypertext link to the principal definition of the set; all you need to do is click on that entry to see it.
	For example: in the original dictionary the word ka ca is given followed by the word ka cha and both are grouped together with the same definition nor dngos po spyi?i ming /  ?a general term for possession, things of value to the owner?.  i) The two words have been separated and put into correct alphabetical order so they are no longer seen one after the other.  ii) The headword ka ca was selected as the prime term (for grammatical reasons).  The headword ka ca was thus given the definition nor dngos po spyi?i ming /.  Then, the headword entry ka cha was given the definition ka ca dang don ?brel ba/ where the blue colour shows a hypertext entry back to the principal term and the dang don ?brel ba/ should be understood to mean that that is what has been done.

	Note again that these sets of headwords sometimes really do have exactly the same meaning.  In other cases, they are similar: the definition is usually exact for one and roughly so for the other.  In other cases the terms are epithets with a different literal meaning that point to the same thing.  In other cases different tenses of one verb are grouped together.  And so on.

	4) Occasionally we have separated multiple meanings by numbering them with 1, 2, and so on to make them clearer, though the original does not have these.

	5) Some entries have the sign [empty or unreadable; ????????????????????????] for the definition.  This means that the definition in the original was empty or unreadable.

	6) Several entries in the original have some words followed by der ltos shig/ which is the equivalent of the Latin ?q.v.? or ?see that (preceding word xxx for the meaning of this term)?.
==DICTIONARY ORDER==
	There are two or three, similar schemes for alphabetizing Tibetan words.  This dictionary is done according to the most common one.  Being a computerised dictionary, there are no divisions within the dictionary itself; it is just one long list.  However, within the word list there are six main levels of ordering the words.  In order from most to least significant they are:
	1.	Head words are alphabetized on the basis of their ming gzhi ?name-base? consonants.  Alphabetization proceeds in the order of the Tibetan syllables: ka kha ga ca cha ja nya ta tha da na pa pha ba ma tsa tsha dza wa zha za ?a ya ra la sha sa ha aa/
	2.	Next, for a given Tibetan syllable, words using just the bare syllable are presented first, followed by words consisting of the syllable plus a vowel sign.  This latter order is in the normal order of the four vowel signs of the Tibetan language: gi gu zhabs kyu ?greng bu na ro (which roughly correspond to the english vowels i u e o respectively).  As each vowel sign is presented, any words with suffices are also presented according to the normal, syllabic order of the suffix.
	3.	Next, the syllable with a sub-scribed letter is presented.  The sub-scribed letters are presented in normal syllabic order, and then in accordance with #2.
	4.	Next, the syllable with a prefix letter is presented.  The prefixes are presented in normal syllabic order, and then in accordance with number #2 and #3.
	5.	Next, the syllable with a superscribed head-letter is presented.  The superscribed letters are presented in the normal syllabic order, and then in accordance with #2 to #4.
	6.	Sanskrit transliterated into Tibetan is alphabetized according to the order of Tibetan syllables as mentioned in #1 to #5 but is also done in the left to right fashion of Sanskrit within a word where necessary.  Sanskrit vowels, which include a subscribed a chung and so on are ordered after the end of a normal Tibetan sequence.  Thus, the word k?a will appear after ka.  However, the unusual letter combinations which do not appear in normal Tibetan writing, such as kSha, are ordered as though they were normal Tibetan combinations.  So, for instance, the word kShetra p?a la would appear in order after the words withkla as their (ming gzhi) name-base and gha would appear in order after words with gla as their name-base.
==TIBETAN TRANSLITERATION SYSTEM==
	Different methods for representing Tibetan letters using the English alphabet have been employed since the early 1800?s.  In the 1940?s Turrell Wylie published an academic paper with a system for transliterating Tibetan into English.  His system has been widely adopted and is called ?Wylie? transliteration.  Unfortunately, other schemes have been invented and persist, so there is no one standard for transliteration.

The Wylie transliteration system for the Tibetan vowels is as follows:
	??	 a	???	i 	???	 u	??	e	???	o

The Wylie transliteration system for the Tibetan consonants is as follows:
	??	ka	??	kha	??	ga	??	nga
	??	ca	??	cha	??	ja	??	nya
	??	ta	??	tha	??	da	??	na
	??	pa	??	pha	??	ba	??	ma
	??	tsa	??	tsha	??	dza	??	wa
	??	zha	??	za	??	'a	??	ya
	??	ra	??	la	??	sha	??	sa
	??	ha	??	a

Note how all of the consonants are represented by one to three English consonants followed by a vowel except for the last consonant which is just written as a vowel.  The writing of the last consonant, called an achen, with only a single vowel is the one mistake in Wylie?s scheme.  By not representing the consonant with one letter followed by a vowel, his system cannot distinguish between ??? and ???, both of which are valid combinations in the Tibetan system.  His system results in these two different combinations appearing indistinguishably as a'a.  To resolve this, we have (done what some others have done and) made the transliteration of the achen into ?aa?; the first letter always represents the consonant and the second represents the vowel.  In this system ??? becomes a'a and ??? becomes aa'a so that there is no ambiguity.

When the vowels are added to a consonant, the vowel letter is changed according to the consonant added.  Thus, for the first consonant, letter ?? ka:
	???	ki	???	ku	???	ke	???	ko
	
Wylie?s system, with the modification given for the achen, makes a system that can accurately represent all grammatically correct forms of written Tibetan.  However, Wylie?s system has no means for representing Sanskrit transliterated into Tibetan and has no system for representing punctuation, both of which are needed for representing written Tibetan in English.  Thus we have added extensions for Sanskrit transliterated into Tibetan and punctuation.

Our complete system for representing written Tibetan is as follows.

1) The thirty Tibetan consonants without an explicit vowel are as follows:
	??	ka	??	kha	??	ga	??	nga
	??	ca	??	cha	??	ja	??	nya
	??	ta	??	tha	??	da	??	na
	??	pa	??	pha	??	ba	??	ma
	??	tsa	??	tsha	??	dza	??	wa
	??	zha	??	za	??	'a	??	ya
	??	ra	??	la	??	sha	??	sa
	??	ha	??	aa

E.g., The first Tibetan consonant with each of the standard four Tibetan vowels:
		???	ki	???	ku	???	ke	???	ko

Note the last Tibetan consonant with each of the vowels:
		??	aa	???	ai 	???	au	??	ae	???	ao

2) The sixteen Sanskrit vowels transliterated into Tibetan then transliterated into English are as follows:
	??	aa	???	a'a	???	ai	????	a'i 	???	au	???	a'u
	???	rI	????	r'I	???	li	????	l'I
	??	ae	???	aai	???	ao	???	aau
	??	aM	??	aH
	For example:
		???	k'a	????	k'i	???	k'u	????	krI	?????	kr'I
		???	kai	???	kau	???	kaM	????	k'aM	??	kaH
		?????	a'oM	???	aau	????	aauM	

3) The application of a ????????? halanta is shown with the forward slash ?/?.  And the application of a   ? chandrabindu is shown with ?(M?.
For example:
	????	phaT/	???	pa(M

4) The five Sanskrit retroflex letters transliterated into Tibetan are as follows:
	??	Ta	??	Tha	??	Da	??	Na	??	Sha	??? kSha

5) The aspirated Sanskrit consonants transliterated into Tibetan are as follows:
	???	gha	???	Dha	??-	dha	??-	bha	???	dzha

6) Ambiguous stacks:
	A few very rare but correct Tibetan stacks from ????????? ?old orthography? and any compound Sanskrit stacks that would be ambiguously transliterated with the above system are transliterated using a + sign to remove the ambiguity.  The plus sign is only used where ambiguity would result.
	For example, in old Tibetan:
		e? is transliterated as ?s+ho?
	For example in Sanskrit transliterated into Tibetan:
		????	?ggha? does not need a plus sign because the transliteration is not ambiguous;
		???	g+nya does need a plus sign because gnya is ambiguous; 
		??-	n+ya does need a plus sign because nya is ambiguous (it could be ?? or ??-).
		??????	seng+ge does need a plus sign because sengge is ambiguous, etc.

7) Punctuation:
	i) Tshegs: Tshegs are represented by a space ? ?. 
	ii) Shad: Shad are represented by a vertical bar ?|?.
	iii) Spaces: Spaces are represented by spaces ? ?.

'gyur/  /de bas rmongs pa sel ba'i phyir/  /mgon pos ming du btags par mdzad/  /ces gsungs/  kun mkhyen dbyig gnyen gyis/  de thams cad kyi rnam par bzhag pa'ang ming yin pas de'i mtha' yang brjod par bya ste zhes dang /  sum cu pa las/  bslab pa kun gyi gzhi 'dzin cing /  /rig byed smra ba rnams kyi rgyu/  /ming tshig brjod pa kun gyi gzhi/  /mi ge'i sbyor ba zhes dang /  rtags kyi 'jug pa las/  ming tshig gsal bar med na ni/  /don rnams brjod par mi 'gyur ro/  /zhes gsungs/  rje btsun sa paN gyis/  lung ston par byed pa sgra'i gnas ma rtogs pas ni/  /tshig gi sdeb sbyor tsam yang shes par mi 'gyur na/  /yang dag pa'i don rtogs par ga la 'gyur zhes dang /  dpal sgang lo ts'a bas/  /ae ma shes bya pha mtha' yas/  /de dag re re'i ming gi yang /  /rgyu mtshan nges tshig mi shes na/  /brda dag sbyor ba ji ltar 'byung /  /zhes dang /  so so rig bzhi sa dgu pa/  /ma thob de srid chos kun gyi/  /nges tshig shes ming de yi phyir/  /mtha' dag sdeb sbyor su yi shes/  /'on kyang phyogs re'i brda dag kyang /  /'bad pa du mas btsal bar bya/  /yi ge'i sbyor ba la 'khrul na/  /don rnams 'khrul ba smos ci dgos/  /zhes gsungs pa dang /  rgyal sras thogs med bzang pos/  spyir ming btags pa tsam gyi dgos pa ni don go ba ste/  zhes dang /  rje byams pa gling pas/  'di ni mkhas pa'i phyi mo ste/  /de phyir thog mar de nyid bslab/  /'di tsam kho nas mang po'i don/  /ston pa'i mkhan po med kyang shes/  /zhes dang /  rgyal ba lnga pa chen pos/  tshig don la 'khrul ba tshar gcod brda sprod dang gtan tshigs/  gzhan la phan zhing rjes su 'dzin par byed pa bzo dang gso ba/  rang nyid chos kun shes par byed pa nang don rig pa ste/  lnga po 'di ni khong du chud pa la 'phags pa'i yul du ma h'a paNDi ta zhes grags shing /  lnga po de'i nang nas kyang thog mar bslab par bya ba ni/  thog mar sgra la mkhas pa yis/  /tshig don rnam par phye ste bstan/  /de nas don la mkhas pa yis/  /lhag chad 'khrul ba med par bshad/  /ces dang yang sgra shes na don la mi rmongs pas rjod byed kun gyi gzhir bzung ba'i steng du/  snyan dngags shes na tshig rgyan la mi rmongs/  sdeb sbyor shes na tshigs bcad la mi rmongs/  mngon brjod shes na ming la mi rmongs/  zlos gar shes na skad rig la mi rmongs shing sogs gsungs pa dang /  rje 'jam dbyangs bzhad pas/  chos thams cad 'jog pa yang ming la rag las pas/  zhes gsungs pa dang /  mkhas pa la las/  ji skad du/  gang zhig tshig la the tshom za gyur pa/  /de yi don ni ji ltar rtogs par 'gyur/  /zhes dang /  brda la brten nas don 'tshol phyir/  /ming brda 'phrad pa shin tu gces/  /zhes dang ming btags pa ni don go ba'i ched yin la/  zhes dang rin spungs pa ngag dbang 'jig grags kyis/  ae ma chos kyi gnas lugs mtha' dag don/  /rtogs byed dang po ming gi brda sprod pa/  /zhes dang /  dag byed gsal ba'i me long las/  gsung rab brda la ma sbyangs na/  /rjod byed tshig gi sgra 'dra yang /  /brjod bya don la khyad par yod/  /de phyir yi ge'i dag byed dgos/  /zhes gsungs pa dang /  nyer mkho sgron gsal las/  /bka' dang bstan bcos zab rgya che'i/  /don rnams smos ci 'jig rten gyi/  /ming tshig brjod don rnam dag kyang /  /'dod na yi ge'i sdeb sbyor gces/  /zhes dang /  mkhas pa la las/  yi ge'i brda la brten nas ni/  /ma nor don rnams 'tshol dgos phyir/  /zhes dang /  rnam dag brda sprod gzhung lugs la/  /ma sbyangs rmongs pa'i pho tshod kyis/  /'chad rtsod rtsom pa'i khur 'khyer ba/  /gang de ngal bar ma gyur tam/  /sgra shes don la mi rmongs shes/  /mkhas pa'i gtam du grags pa na/  /zhes sogs dang /  ming don sbyor ba shes pa'i mig ldan dang /  /brda la sbyangs pa med pa'i dmus long gnyis/  /thos bsam sgom pa'i bshul ring lam bgrod tshe/  /mchog dman khyad par che ba kun gyis shes/  /zhes sogs ming mi shes par don ma rtogs pa'i sgrub byed dang /  /yang na phyis gsar thon dngos po rnams dper na lcags skud brda dang lcags skud med brda'am rlung 'phrin brda dang gnam gru dang phyogs brtag 'khor lo sogs la ming gsar du btags pa'am 'dogs rung ste/  rje btsun sa paN gyis/  brda sprod pa'i mkhas pa dag gis brda gsar pa ma sbyar na/  don ma 'grub pa mthong na/  gsar pa sbyar ba mi 'gal mod/  'on kyang dgos pa chung ngu la brda gsar mi sbyor te/  ma rtogs pa dang log par rtog pa dang the tshom gyi rgyu yin pa'i phyir ro/  /zhes gsungs so/  /
==Preface > ming du btags pa'i tshul lugs==
@@/  /rje sa paN gyis 'dod rgyal gyi ming dang /  rjes sgrub kyi ming ngo /  /dang po ni chos gang la/  de med bzhin du btags pa ste dper na bum pa dang ka ba la sogs pa bzhin no/  /de gzhan la ma ltos pa'i phyir nges tshig sgrub tu med de chos nyid bzhin no/  /rjes su sgrub pa la gnyis/  don dang ldan pa'i rjes sgrub dang /  log par sgrub pa'i rjes sgrub bo/  /dang po la gnyis te/  mtshan nyid dang /  dbye ba'o/  /dang po ni gzhan la ltos pa dang /  bcas nas don yang dag par sgrub pa ste/  dper na 'bras bu'i rtags kyis rgyu dpog pa na gang du du ba yod pa na me yod de/  dper na tshang mang bzhin sa phyogs che ge mo na yang du ba yod pa'i phyir me yod do zhes 'thad pa sgrub pa na skyes bus pha rol na me yod par nges so/  /de bzhin du dung 'di ni dkar la khyi 'di yang dkar ba'i phyir/  khyi 'di la yang ming dung zhes brjod pa lta bu'o/  /de phan chad kyi tshig ni sgrub par mi 'os pa ste dung dkar ba'i 'thad pa dang /  /me las du ba byung ba la sogs pa'i 'thad pa la sogs pa ha cang thal ba'i phyir ro/  /spyi don gnyis pa dbye na gnyis te/  ngo bo nyid kyi ming dang /  btags pa'i ming ngo /  /dang po la gnyis te/  mtshan nyid dang /  dbye ba'o/  /mtshan nyid ni/  gzhan la ma ltos par rang gi ngo bo bsgrubs pa'o/  /gnyis pa dbye ba la gsum ste/  yin par sgrub pa dang /  ngo bo sgrub pa dang /  dngos po'i rkyen sgrub pa'o/  /dang po la'ang gnyis te/  mtshan nyid dang /  dbye ba'o/  /mtshan nyid ni ngo bo bsgrub cing gzhan par zur mi za ba'o/  /gnyis pa ngo bo bsgrub pa ni rang gi rdzas bsgrub pa ste/  dper na me ni me'o zhes brjod pa na yod pa la sogs pa btags pa'i ming lnga spong ba'o/  /gsum pa dngos po'i rkyen sgrub pa ni/  rang gi ldog pa phyogs gcig bsgrub pa ste/  dper na me ni gsal ba'o zhes brjod pa na/  tsha ba la sogs pa'i ldog pa gzhan sel ba'o/  /gnyis pa btags pa'i ming la gnyis/  mtshan nyid dang /  dbye ba'o/  /dang po ni don gzhan gyi cha tsam la brten nas bsgrub pa'o/  /dbye na bzhi ste/  rten la brten par btags pa dang /  rgyu la 'bras bu btags pa dang /  'bras bu la rgyur btags pa dang /  'dra ba dngos su btags pa'o/  /dang po la gnyis te/  rdzas tha dad ldog pa gcig la brten pa dang /  ldog pa tha dad rdzas gcig la brten pa'o/  /dang po ni/  sa bon 'debs pa la zhing 'debs pa lta bu'am mi ngan gyi rten byas pa la mi ngan lta bu'o/  /gnyis pa ni yon tan yod pa la yon tan can nam/  rtsal yod pa la rtsal can lta bu'o/  /rgyu la 'bras bur btags pa la gnyis te/  brgyud pa'i rgyu la 'bras bur btags pa dang /  dngos kyi rgyu la 'bras bur btags pa'o/  dang po ni lud la zas yin zhes pa lta bu'am/  sman la srog yin zhes pa lta bu'o/  /gnyis pa ni/  yos 'thags pa la phye 'thags pa lta bu'am/  sman srog yin pa lta bu'o/  /'bras bu la rgyur btags pa ni/  me byed pa la me shing lta bu'o/  /'dra ba la dngos kyi ming btags pa la'ang gnyis/  rdzas 'dra ba dang /  ldog pa 'dra ba'o/  /dang po ni/  sems can la sangs rgyas zhes bshad pa lta bu'o/  /gnyis pa ni/  skyes bu mdzes pa la lha zhes brjod pa lta bu'o/  /btags pa'i ming bstan zin to/  /don dang ldan pa'i rjes sgrub bshad zin to/  /de ni spyi don gnyis pa log par bsgrub pa'i rjes bsgrub ston to/  /de la gnyis te/  mtshan nyid dang /  khyad par ro/  /dang po ni gzhan la ltos nas rang gi ngo bo log par sgrub pa ste/  dper na khyi nag po la dung zhes brjod pa bzhin te/  nges tshig yod mod kyang log par sgrub pa'i phyir mi bshad do/  /gnyis pa khyad par ni/  'o na nges tshig bshad du med pa'i phyir 'dod rgyal ba dang khyad par ci yod ce na/  nges tshig bshad du med pa tsam la khyad par med mod kyang /  'dod rgyal ba ni/  don gzhan la ma brten pa yin la 'di ni gzhan la brten pa min no/  /ming gi tshogs bstan zin to/  /zhes gsungs pa//  //

„Ã	karsha pa na'i zur chag ste dngul zho'i dong tse dang la las 'gron bu'i ming dang mtsho D'ik tu dngul zho phyed las byas pa'i dong tse'i rnam pa 'dra ba dang / rnam 'byed las/ ma sha ka lnga ni karsha pa ni'i bzhi cha'i dpe yin par gsungs pa dang / yang na de la dngos dang ming du btags pa tsam gnyis/ dang po ni dngul gyi dong tse dang gnyis pa de'i rin gyi 'gron bu'o/ /karsha pa/

==skya rengs dang po==
„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	'od ldan las/ skya rengs dang po shar na ni/ shar phyogs su ni sngor snang zhing / skar ma'i gdong ni 'od nyams pa/ nam mkha' sngo skyar 'gyur ba yin/ skya rengs bar ma shar na ni/ de ni shar phyogs skya zhing dmar/ rgyu dkar 'od ni chung ba dang / nam mkha' ser skya 'gyur ba yin/ skya rengs tha ma shar na ni/ rgyu dkar 'od ni med pa dang / skya rengs tha ma'o zer ba bshad/ 'o zis nyi ma shar bar du'o/  skya rengs bar ma dang don 'brel ba/  skya rengs tha ma dang don 'brel ba/
==skya rengs ldan pa==
„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	mtho rengs sam tho rengs ming /
==skya rengs nu bo==
„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	mkha' lding ngam khyab 'jug bzhon pa/ skya rengs dmar/ skya rengs dkar/ skya rengs ser/ skya rengs dang po shar ba/ skya rengs bar ma shar ba/ skya rengs tha ma/

„Ã	thug pa'i bye brag dang yang skyo ma la phra ma'am zer/  skyo ma dang don 'brel ba/  skyo tsha dang don 'brel ba/
==skyo 'dur==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	thug pa'i bye
==skyo ba==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	yid 'byung ba'am dga' ba med pa sems skyo ba dang skyo zhes pa'i yul la'ang /  skyo shas dang don 'brel ba/
==skyo ma==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	skyo thang dang don 'brel ba/
==skyo ma snga btsan==
„Ã	??????????????
„Ã	sngar phra ma'am 'thab rtsod pa'i tshe phyir de ltar mi rtsod pa'i btsan po'i chad pas bcad pa'i don/

„Ã	gzhan rgyu mtshan du byas nas nyes spyod la 'dzems pa'i shes pa'o/  khrel gzhung dang don 'brel ba/
==khres po==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	gcig tu sbrags pa'i khur po lta bu/
==khres po sgros shig==
„Ã	??????????????????
„Ã	khur po mnyam du khres por gyis
==khro==
„Ã	????

„Ã	dbyar tha ma'am hor zla bdun pa dang seng ge'i khyim la'ang /  gro bzhin zla ba dang don 'brel ba/
==gro bzhin zla ba==
„Ã	??????????????
„Ã	gro bzhin can dang don 'brel ba/
==gro lam res chod==
„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	gro lam re res sleb pa'i don/
==gro lung pa==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	yul zhig gi mi/

„Ã	????????

==grog mkhar==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	srog chags grog ma'i tshang zhing /  grog tshang dang don 'brel ba/  grog zhing dang don 'brel ba/

„Ã	??????????????????

„Ã	ma 'grig pa'am mi rigs pa/
==cho 'phrul==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	dang po nyid du gdul bya'i yid 'phrog par byed pas na cho 'phrul zhes gsungs/
==cho 'phrul gsum==
„Ã	??????????????
„Ã	rdzu 'phrul gyi cho 'phrul ni rdzu 'phrul gyi mngon shes lta bu ngad kun brjod pa'i cho 'phrul ni sems kyi rnam grangs shes pa dang rjes su bstan pa'i cho 'phrul ni zag zad mngon shes lta bu'o/

„Ã	sangs rgyas kyi mtshan/

==nya pa==
„Ã	????

==nya phyis==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	mu tig gi shun pa'am/
==nya phyis sa bon==
„Ã	?????????????
„Ã	mu tig gam grol ba/  nya lcibs skyes dang don 'brel ba/
==nya 'phar==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	chu nas 'phar mchongs pa lta bu/
==nya bo==
„Ã	?????

„Ã	??????

„Ã	?????
„Ã	nya dang don 'brel ba/
==nya tshang==
„Ã	?????
„Ã	mu tig 'byung gnas kyi ming dang chu bal lam nya 'khebs pa'i rtsva zhig ste rnam byed 'grel ba las nya lcibs zhes bya ni chu na 'phyo ba'i rdzas so zhes dang nya tshang zhes bya ba ni nya lcibs 'dra ba'i chu'i rtsva yin zhes gsungs/  nya lcibs dang don 'brel ba/  nya skyob dang don 'brel ba/

==nyams==
„Ã	????
„Ã	1) sgeg pa'i nyams la sogs pa dgu ste snyan ngag dang mkhas 'jug la ltos shig
	2) rdzig po'am yon tan med la nyams tsha po'am chen po lta bu/
==nyams khrid==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	zhi lhag gi don bya'i ngo sprod lta bu'am blang dor bslab pa khrid mdzad pa lta bu/
==nyams dga' ba==
„Ã	??????????

==nyams dgu==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	sgeg pa'i nyams la sogs pa dgu snyan ngag dang mkhas 'jug la ltos shig/
==nyams mgur==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	don rtogs pa'i glu/
==nyams rgud pa==
„Ã	???????????
„Ã	lus stobs nyams pa'am blo stobs zhan par gyur pa lta bu/  nyams dmas pa dang don 'brel ba/
==nyams rgyas==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	lus kyi stobs rgyas pa'am rdzig po'am/ khengs dreg che ba la'ang /  nyams stobs rgyas dang don 'brel ba/  nyams ldan dang don 'brel ba/
==nyams bcos==
„Ã	?????????

„Ã	smyan ka ste bag ma gtong len pa'am gtong len gyi pho nya/ gnyan ldeb dang don 'brel ba/
==gnyen te==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	'brel te'am 'dren te/
==gnyen 'thams pa==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	gnyen tshan du 'brel zhing mthun pa'o/  gnyen 'dun pa dang don 'brel ba/
==gnyen 'dab==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	spun nye du dang bshes gnyen/  gnyen bshes dang don 'brel ba/
==gnyen 'dun pa==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	gnyen 'thams pa dang don 'brel ba/
==gnyen ldeb==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	gnyen ka dang don 'brel ba/
==gnyen po==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	'joms byed de nad kyi gnyen po sman dang khong khro'i gnyen po bzod pa lta bu/
==gnyen byed==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	smyan byed de bag ma gtong len byed po/ smyan byed/
==gnyen yig==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	bag ma gtong len gyi gan rgya/
==gnyen bshes==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	gnyen 'dab dang don 'brel ba/
==gnyer skyed==
„Ã	???????????
„Ã	'chang ba'am nyar tshags skyed/
==gnyer can==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	rgan mo dang /

„Ã	???????????
„Ã	bcol ba'am gnyer du 'jug pa/

„Ã	?????????????
„Ã	dam ngag ston pa po/

„Ã	???????
„Ã	lde mig 'dzin pa dang ched du gnyer pa/

„Ã	???????

„Ã	??????????????

„Ã	?????????

„Ã	?????

„Ã	????????

==gnyod==
„Ã	?????

„Ã	???????

„Ã	?????????

„Ã	????????
„Ã	gnyos dang don 'brel ba/
==mnyan pa==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	na bas thos pa'am skya ba 'dzin pa/ nyan pa/

„Ã	???????
„Ã	sgra ste rjod byed sgra lta bu/

„Ã	????????
„Ã	rgya gar na sh'a bsti zhes pa'i yul/
==mnyam 'jog pa==
„Ã	???????????
„Ã	ting nge 'dzin nam bsam gtan la sems mnyam par 'jog pa'am bzhag pa/  mnyam bzhag dang don 'brel ba/

„Ã	mnyam bzhag dang rjes thob gnyis/
==mnyam nyid==
„Ã	????????

„Ã	???????

==gdos bu==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	mtsho T'i ka las/ shing sogs las byas pa'i gdos bu chu tshod kyi snod 'dra ba chung ngu byas te de lung mig nas skud pas btags te bsam gtan pa rnams gnyid bro na gdos bu de rang gi rna ba la btags te dpyang par bya'o/ /zhes pas de'i nang du chu blugs pas gnyid bro nas g-yo ba na chu 'bo bab pas gnyid sad do/ /gru gzings kyi 'phyar dar/ rlung g-yor/

„Ã	rgyab tu ma yin mdun du lta bu snga rol tu'am gdong ngos su/  mdun rol tu dang don 'brel ba/
==mdun du bcar ba==
„Ã	??????????????
„Ã	sku'i drung du bcar ba lta bu/
==mdun du bsdogs pa==

==mdun na 'don==

==snag gi gnyen mtshams==
„Ã	?????????????????
„Ã	pha ma gcig pa las skyes pa'i spun zla yin par brgyad stong 'grel chen las gsungs pa dang / yang na srin mo'i bu dang bu mo'i bu la snag gi tsha bo zer ba dang / de'i bu la yang tsha zer ba dang / snag dbon ni aa ne'i bu yin pas sring mo'i bu'am/ de dag ni dpyad na snag ces sha'i ming du snang pas rus rigs ma yin pa sha'i rigs su gyur pa'i spun nye du'am/  snag dbon dang don 'brel ba/

„Ã	ri yi ming /  sprin 'dzin dang don 'brel ba/
==sprin grol ma'i khyo ba==
„Ã	?????????????????????
„Ã	sprin dang don 'brel ba/
==sprin mgrin==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	mi spyi'i ming /
==sprin lce==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	sprin gyi lcug ma dang don 'brel ba/
==sprin gtibs pa==
„Ã	??????????????
„Ã	sprin 'thibs su bcug pa'am byas pa/
==sprin mthongs==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	sprin gyi bar mtshams mthongs/
==sprin dus==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	sprin skyes dang don 'brel ba/

„Ã	???????????????????

„Ã	???????????????????
„Ã	dbyar kha'i dus su/

„Ã	?????????????
„Ã	mon
==sprin med==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	bsam gtan bzhi pa'i lha la'ang /
==sprin 'dzin==
„Ã	???????????
„Ã	sprin gyi so can dang don 'brel ba/
==sprin bzang zla ba==
„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	khrums zla dang hor zla brgyad pa la'ang /  sprin legs dang don 'brel ba/
==sprin rum na==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	sprin mtshams na/
==sprin la dga'==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	rma bya'i ming /  sprin la sgeg dang don 'brel ba/

„Ã	???????????

==sprul sku==

„Ã	ri bong gi rgya/
==bong rgyas 'tsho pa==
„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	ri bong la rgya btab pas 'tsho pa/
==bong che chung==
„Ã	???????????
„Ã	gtos che chung gzugs bongs che chung yang /
==bong snyoms==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	sman dug cig dang bong ba dmar po lta bu/  bong dug dang don 'brel ba/
==bong thor==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	bong gu lo gnyis pa/
==bong dug==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	bong snyoms dang don 'brel ba/
==bong ba==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	spo tho'am sa yi gong bu'am sa sra rdog rdog la'ang / bong ma/
==bong ba dkar nag==
„Ã	?????????????
„Ã	sman dug cig dang bong ba dmar po lta bu/
==bong ba nyed pa==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	sa phag gi sa brdzi bar byed pa lta bu/
==bong ba'i rbab==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	la ma lta bu'i sa'i rbab/
==bong bu==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	mgrin bzang ngam dre'u'i pha bong gu/
==bong gu dga'==
„Ã	???????????
„Ã	lcags mo yos lo/
==bong bu rgyas 'chor==
„Ã	?????????????????
„Ã	ri bong rgya yis 'debs pa po/  bong bu rgyas gshor dang don 'brel ba/
==bong bu rgyas gshor==
„Ã	?????????????????
„Ã	bong bu rgyas 'chor dang don 'brel ba/
==bong ma==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	spo tho'am sa yi gong bu'am sa sra rdog rdog la'ang / bong ba/
==bong mi==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	la ma'i me lta bu/
==bong rmed==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	bong gu'i rmed thag pa/
==bong tshad==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	che chung bongs tshad la'ang /
==bong yar==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	da ning phru gu skyes pa'i bong gu/
==bongs che chung==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	bong che chung der ltos shig bong che chung /
==bongs snyoms==
„Ã	???????????
„Ã	che chung cha mnyam pa'i don/
==bod==
„Ã	????
„Ã	bod chen po dang don 'brel ba/
==bod chen po==
„Ã	???????????
„Ã	bod dang don 'brel ba/
==bod yul==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	bod gangs can yul/
==bon==
„Ã	????
„Ã	chu bon lta bu/
==bon sgrung==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	bon po'i chos 'byung rnam thar lta bu/
==bon pa==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	bod pa'am bzlas pa'i don/
==bon pa'i chos==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	ston pa gshen rabs kyi chos te lha 'bod de sha khrag gi mchod pa gtor ba lta bu/
==bor ba==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	dor ba'am dbyugs pa/  bor stor dang don 'brel ba/
==bor stor==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	bor ba dang don 'brel ba/
==bol gong==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	rkang mgo'i 'bol gong /
==bol po==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	'bol po 'jam po/
==bol rtsa==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	rkang mgo'i 'bol gong gi rtsa rgyus lta bu/
==bos pa==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	skad btang ba'am/ 'bod pa/
==bos shig==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	skad thong
==bya==
„Ã	???
„Ã	'dab chags bya dang rus rigs shig byed pa/
==bya kri==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	sman
==bya dkar==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	chu'i bya
==bya rkang==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	me tog cig dang bya'i rkang pa'ang /
==bya skon==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	bya 'dzin byed thabs te bya rkon dang rkon bu zhes pa'ang snang / bya rkon/ rkon bu/
==bya skyibs==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	bya bye'u sdod sa brag gi khung bu lta bu dang khang pa'i mda' yab kyi khyad par/
==bya khyung==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	mkha' lding /
==bya khyung dkar po==
„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	ngang pa la'ang /
==bya khyung rdo==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	mthing gi ming /
==bya khyung dmar po==
„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	ngur pa'am ngang pa dmar po la'ang /
==bya khra==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	bya bye'u gsod mkhan bya/
==bya gag==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	la las chu bya dkar po ske ring po dang 'ga' zhig gis khyim bya dang rna rgyan du khyim bya dang bya gag so sor bshad kho bo'i rnam rtog shar tshod ni bya gag la cha'i bya gag ces rna rgyan du dbye ba logs su gsungs pas 'di la 'dam 'thor zer ba dang chu'i ku kku bha'ang zer ba'o/ /yang bya gag la sa gnas zhes pas sa'i bya gag dang ku ku sgrog ces pas khyim bya bya de yin snyam dbye ba gnyis su phye ba yin/
==bya gag rgyal mtshan==
„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	gdong
==bya glag==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	lu gu 'khyer byed bya nya 'khyer byed chu glag zer ba lta bu/ chu
==bya dga'==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	gsol ras/
==bya rgod==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	mkha' la 'khor byed bya rgod/

„Ã	???????????????
„Ã	sangs rgyas kyis sher phyin gyi mdo gsungs pa'i sa cha ri/
==bya rgya==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	bya bye'u 'dzin thabs thag drva/
==bya rgyud==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	rgyud sde bzhin nang tshan/

„Ã	???????
„Ã	bya ba'i gzhi/

„Ã	????????
„Ã	gshog pa'i sgro/

„Ã	????????????
„Ã	bya 'dab chags can dang gcan gzan gnyis/
==bya mchu==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	khrums stod skar ma dang bya'i mchu sgro/
==bya 'chor==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	bya rgya yis 'chor ba'am gshor mkhan/
==bya gtong==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	'phrin gtong ba la'ang /
==bya btang ba==
„Ã	?????????
„Ã	ri khrod pa'am bsam gtan pa/
==bya thal==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	bya rgod kyi skyag pa/
==bya thi ba==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	phug ron/
==bya de pho mo==
„Ã	????????????
„Ã	khyim bya pho mo zangs ze can ni pho/
==bya 'dab==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	gzhal yas khang gi mda' yab/
==bya na==
„Ã	?????
„Ã	zas kyi tshod ma zhig ste vyanydzana zhes pa'i sran ma'i zur chag /puny+dzana/
==bya na ba==
„Ã	???????
„Ã	tshod ma mkhan/
==bya pa==
„Ã	?????
„Ã	chu bya sogs gsod mkhan/  bya gshor ba dang don 'brel ba/
==bya spangs==
„Ã	????????
„Ã	mtshan mo/

„Ã	????????????

„Ã	??????

„Ã	????????????
„Ã	bya de pho'i/  bya zi dang don 'brel ba/
==bya ba==
„Ã	?????
„Ã	las ka bya ba spyod lam/
==bya bang==
„Ã	??????
„Ã	kra yi sgra can bya zhig gam pho rog che ba'am bya rog rgan pa/  bya rog che ba dang don 'brel ba/

„Ã	????????
„Ã	chu nang gi bal lta bu rtsva/

„Ã	?????????????????

„Ã	???????
„Ã	skra med pa dang gzhan gyi bud med la log g-yem byed po/ rgyan dang bral ba'i don dang gan T'i byi bo brdung zer ba dang pho 'phyon dang byi 'u zer la'ang / byi pho/

„Ã	mtsho T'ika las srog gi dbang po tshe yin te drod dang rnam shes rigs mthun rgyu ba'i rten gang yin pa'o/ /zhes dang mdzod las kyang ngo / /mdo sde pa yan chad du rlung yin par 'dod/  srog dbang dang don 'brel ba/
==srog 'gro==
„Ã	??????????
„Ã	'chi ba'i ming / srog 'dor/
